The Hebb rule states that the final weight matrix W is the sum of the outer products of the target and input vectors for each pattern: W = Σ(T^T * S).

1.  Calculate the weight matrix for pattern 1 (w1):
    w1 = T1^T * S1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} [1, 0, 1, 0] = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}

2.  Calculate the weight matrix for pattern 2 (w2):
    w2 = T2^T * S2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} [1, 0, 0, 1] = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}

3.  Calculate the weight matrix for pattern 3 (w3):
    w3 = T3^T * S3 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} [1, 1, 0, 0] = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 1 & 1 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}

4.  Sum the individual weight matrices to get the final weight matrix W:
    W = w1 + w2 + w3 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 1 & 1 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & 0 & 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 1 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}
